shared_text:
Deanne Austin is with Kalita Jones.
June 7, 2019 at 6:33 PM ·

This past week my team (Lucy Ann Martin, Romeka R. Mack, Denise Robertson, Jay TheMaestro Rashaad, Tracie Green-Brown, and Tiwari McLain) and I had the opportunity to attend the 2019 Making Connections Conference and presenting before teachers all over the state in Biloxi. They each had their own session and when I say Yazoo City High represented well, they were phenomenal. I can’t be more proud of them. As an African American female educator/administrator I believe the best way to build up your teachers/team is to provide them the opportunity to grow and learn. Trailblazers did it for me and plan to continue to pay it forward. Mississippi has some great teachers/educators and I’m proud that some of the greatest are on my team!!!

post_text:
The Yazoo City Municipal School District is holding its Annual Title I meeting on October 18, 2018. The meeting will start at 6:00 in the Yazoo City High School cafeteria. Come out to hear the plans the district has developed for the use of Title I funds. Also, each school principal will present how they plan to use Title I funds for their schools.
As part of the Annual Title I meeting, parents will be provided a compact to begin to forge a positive relationship between the schools and parents. Parents will also have the opportunity to participate in the district development of the Parent and Family Engagement Policy.
Should you have any questions regarding the meeting, please contact Frederick Hill, Federal Program Director, at 662-746-2125 or any principal in the district at their schools. We look forward to seeing you on October 18th.

post_text: Business and industry leaders of Yazoo City joined the staff of the Larry Summers Career and Technical Center last night for their annual craft committee meeting. Director Gregg Giles explained the primary purpose of the career and technical center is to teach scholars skills that will make them productive citizens…skills that will enable them to enter the workforce or to continue training in their chosen fields. Thanks to everyone who came out to support our school as we strive to prepare our scholars for workforce demands.

post_text: Webster Elementary School welcomed guest readers today to celebrate Read Across America Day!

post_text: Webster Elementary School celebrated Read Across America Day with rhyming words, striped hats and a visit from the Cat in the Hat. Students decorated classrooms, donned costumes and enjoyed their visit from the Cat in the Hat while listening to the guest reader. Dr. Antwon Woods, Professor at Belhaven University and President and CEO of the Antwon and Constance Woods Family Foundation, helped the students of Webster kick off Read Across America Day and National Reading Month. Dr. Woods dressed as the Cat in the Hat and read some of his favorite Dr. Seuss books. Both the students of Webster and Dr. Woods were thrilled about their day with the Cat in the Hat. Dr. Woods is dedicated to the promise and opportunity that reading provides children and committed to inspiring a passion for reading among all children.

post_text: From Superintendent Dr. Darron L. Edwards: “The Yazoo City Municipal School District, specifically Yazoo City High School, received a false alarm yesterday which posed a potential threat to the safety of our students. In an effort to always provide the highest level of safety for schools and students, we executed our safety/crisis plan which resulted in ‘NO-INCIDENTS.’ As your Superintendent, I want to take this moment to thank all the parents and community for trusting our district to provide the ultimate level of safety for the children of the Yazoo City Municipal School District.”

post_text: We will be closed next week for Thanksgiving Holiday and will resume Monday, November 27th. As we reflect on the many things for which we are thankful, we would like to take a moment to express how truly thankful we are for the students who come to school every day ready to learn. We are thankful for the support of the parents in creating an outstanding partnership with our district and we are thankful for the teachers and staff who care about our students and their success. The Yazoo City School District wishes all of you and your families a happy, healthy and relaxing Thanksgiving holiday!

The Yazoo City School District wishes all of you and your families a happy, healthy and relaxing Thanksgiving holiday!

post_text: Yazoo City High School was recognized for maintaining 100 years of continuous accreditation from the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Council on Accreditation and School Improvement. SACS CASI, an accreditation division for AdvancED, assists schools and school systems through the accreditation process and helps those institutions demonstrate a continuous commitment to providing quality education programs that are aimed at improving student performance.

post_text: Woolfolk’s Breakfast Club: Members of the community come to the school two or three times a month to eat breakfast and fellowship with our scholars. The goal of the Breakfast Club is to develop the entire child and to encourage them to be productive citizens in their community.

post_text: REMINDER: Registration begins July 18th. We will register from July 18 - July 28th. See the posted list for items to bring with you. The residency documentations are listed in three groups. Bring items from two DIFFERENT groups. For example, if you use your light bill as one proof, pick an item from another group such as an apartment lease for your second proof.

Attention WOOLFOLK and HIGH SCHOOL BETA Club and National Honor Society parents: I will be contacting you about your children volunteering to help with school registration next week. I will be reaching out to those who signed up a few weeks back. If you don’t receive a call or couldn’t make it to the signup, it’s not too late! If your HIGH SCHOOL or MIDDLE SCHOOL child is interested in receiving volunteer hours for Beta Club or NHS, please give me a call on Thursday or Friday at 662-746-7642. WE APPRECIATE YOUR HELP AND SUPPORT!!
--- Adrienne Dee Parker, Technology Coordinator
